snippet.textDisplay:
The main pros in m opinion would be that possibly more advanced programs get supported on mobile devices since most modern mobile programs lack options and customizabilty.
in the Ideal scenario it becomes easy to install nearly any Linux distro on any arm device just like it works on x86 and x64 and some arm devices now.
since you could already 3+ years buy a smartphone with 4gb ram and a 10 core cpu running at 2,5 ghz for around €120 which despite most of those cpu's having a low IPC are still verry energy efficient and quite capable of rendering.
so if you have your phone like a laptop and run a powerfull os like most GNU/Linux distro's on it than you would have a decently powerful system for video editing since epecially well designed programs like Blender schale really well and so also have great multicore support.

Anything you connect your phone to could be a possible threat, putting viruses on your phone or saving data from your phone on a chip, no matter if wired or via great wifi. Which is the sole reason why I would not use such an offer and why I don't think, such a concept will ever turn into some kind of a standard.
The wifi and bluetooth on my phone are always turned off, unless I want to connect to my home wifi or any trusted source, that I know.

snippet.textDisplay:
Thats actually an amazing idea and this would be awesome for my work :D

I do onsite IT, I run my life with my phone and the majority of the time I need a laptop its a case of "My phone can do this but a bigger screen a better mouse would be a big help". It beats a dedicated laptop too because usually all the files I need to do what Im trying to do are usually...on my phone. Being able to do everything on and have it all saved to the device I already use for everything would be a god send.

As would the battery life and how thin it is with basically nothing in it.

It would also be great for those "I just need some files off it but the screen is broken and I dont have a monitor" jobs that inevitable crop up.
